Question 1: What is control flow in JavaScript? Explain how if-else statements work withan example.
ans:-

- Definition:
Control flow in JavaScript means the order in which code is executed in a program 

It helps us write logic:
â€œIf this happens, do that... otherwise do something else.â€

    --- If-else Statement ---

ðŸ”¹ Definition:
if-else is a conditional statement that runs different blocks of code depending on whether a condition is true or false.

ðŸ”¹ Syntax:
if (condition) {
  // runs if condition is true
} else {
  // runs if condition is false
}

ðŸ”¹ Example:

let marks = 75;

if (marks >= 90) {
  console.log("Grade: A");
} else if (marks >= 75) {
  console.log("Grade: B");
} else if (marks >= 60) {
  console.log("Grade: C");
} else {
  console.log("Fail");
}

ðŸ”¹ Output:

Grade: B

Question 2: Describe how switch statements work in JavaScript. When should you use a
switch statement instead of if-else?
ans:-

           ---- Switch Statements ----
Definition:
A switch statement is used to compare a single expression against multiple possible values (called cases).
Itâ€™s a cleaner alternative to writing many if-else if blocks.

ðŸ”¹ Syntax:

switch (expression) {
  case value1:
    // runs if expression === value1
    break;
  case value2:
    // runs if expression === value2
    break;
  default:
    // runs if no case matches
}

ðŸ”¹ Example:

let fruit = "apple";

switch (fruit) {
  case "banana":
    console.log("Yellow fruit");
    break;
  case "apple":
    console.log("Red fruit");
    break;
  case "orange":
    console.log("Orange fruit");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Unknown fruit");
}
ðŸ”¹ Output:

Red fruit


